meanings.text: to draw away from its ordinary position
transitive, obsolete: to draw or conduct away; to withdraw; to draw to a different part
to abduce, to abduct (draw away from the median axis of the body)
(physiology, anatomy) to abduce, to abduct (draw away from the median axis of the body)

examples.first: Quizá por la persona que quieran abducir ahora
examples.second: Maybe with whoever it is they' re looking to abduct next

examples.first: Sean o no sean alienígenas, ¿cómo podrían abducir a tantos después de cinco años?
examples.second: Aliens or no aliens, why would our people return after five years, to be abducted?

examples.first: Sean o no sean alienígenas,¿ cómo podrían abducir a tantos después de cinco años?
examples.second: Aliens or no aliens, why would our people return after five years, to be abducted?

examples.first: Usaste el jet de la compañía para abducir al programador de una Casa rival.
examples.second: You used the company jet to abduct the programmer of a rival House.

examples.first: Bueno, si fuesemos a abducir a uno de tus hijos, seguro que no sería Max.
examples.second: Well, if we were to abduct one of your children, it certainly wouldn't be Max.

examples.first: ¿Por qué abducir a una niña de los 40... retenerla durante 60 años... y devolverla con la capacidad... de predecir el futuro?
examples.second: Why disappear a little girl from the 1940s, hold her for 60 years, and then send her back with the ability to predict the future?

examples.first: Nada de control mental alienígena, nada de invadir cuerpos, ni planes para abducir, digamos, a Max.
examples.second: No alien mind-melding, no body-snatching, no plans to abduct, say, Max.

examples.first: Pensaba que iban a abducir a los niños.
examples.second: Oh, I thought they were gonna abduct the children.

examples.first: Debes haber considerado la posibilidad... de que la hayan vuelto a abducir.
examples.second: You must have considered the possibility that she was abducted again.
